{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2484"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2484"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.19,0.02,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for confirmation of pregnancy. Her last menstrual period was six weeks ago. She describes nausea, lower back pain for six days, and increased urinary frequency for one week. She has a regular 28-day menstrual cycle. She is sexually active with her long-term partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history apart from adequately treated chlamydia infection four years ago. Her last cervical screening test was five years ago with normal results. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A cervical screening test is performed and antenatal investigations are arranged. Ultrasound confirms a single live intrauterine pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical screening test results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV 16/18: detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV (not 16/18): not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiquid-based cytology: possible low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndocervical component: identified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Early referral for colposcopy during pregnancy","Referral for postpartum colposcopy","Repeat HPV test in six weeks","Repeat HPV test in 12 months","Schedule next screening test in five years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had HPV 16/18 detected on routine cervical screening during early pregnancy. The presence of high-risk HPV types (16/18) requires immediate action regardless of the liquid-based cytology (LBC) results. \u003Cstrong\u003EEarly referral for colposcopy during pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is essential and safe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for postpartum colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E would inappropriately delay assessment of a high-risk finding. While certain treatments may need to be deferred until after delivery, colposcopic assessment should not be delayed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat HPV test in six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate when HPV 16/18 is detected. Immediate colposcopy is required rather than repeat testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat HPV test in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for non-16/18 HPV types with negative cytology or possible low-grade changes, but not for HPV 16/18.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchedule next screening test in five years\u003C/strong\u003E is only appropriate when HPV is not detected. Any positive HPV result requires more frequent surveillance or immediate colposcopy depending on the type detected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECervical screening during pregnancy is safe when performed with a cervical sampler (avoiding endocervical brush). The presence of pregnancy does not change the management algorithm for high-risk HPV detection, though some treatments may need to be deferred until after delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HPV 16/18 detection on cervical screening requires immediate colposcopy referral regardless of LBC results","Cervical screening can be safely performed during pregnancy using a cervical sampler (not endocervical brush)","Routine cervical screening should be performed every five years from age 25-74 unless oncogenic HPV is detected"],"references":["National Cervical Screening Program \u2013 Understanding the National Cervical Screening Program Management Pathway: a Guide for healthcare providers. In: National Cervical Screening Program [online]. 2022; accessed 2023 Apr. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/national-cervical-screening-program-understanding-the-national-cervical-screening-program-management-pathway?language=en","Peirson L, Fitzpatrick-Lewis D, Ciliska D, Warren R. Screening for cervical cancer: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Syst Rev 2013;2:35. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23706117/","Screening in pregnancy. National Cervical Screening Program: Guidelines for the management of screen-detected abnormalities, screening in specific populations and investigation of abnormal vaginal bleeding. In: Australian Cancer Council Clinical Guidelines Network [online]. Accessed 2023 Apr 1. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer-screening/screening-in-pregnancy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2484"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T19:39:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T19:39:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2484"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Prac